This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a novel approach for imitation learning using Wasserstein Adversarial Imitation Learning. The paper also discusses the use of Optimal Transport, which is a well-known technique in machine learning. Additionally, the paper presents experimental results on robotic tasks, which is a common application area for machine learning.

The paper also touches upon the use of reward functions, which is a common topic in the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The use of Kantorovich potentials as a reward function is also related to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision), which often deals with image-based tasks and the use of distance metrics.

The paper's focus on robotic experiments and the use of optimal transport suggests that it may also belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.RO (Robotics). Finally, the paper's discussion of sample efficiency and large-scale applications suggests that it may also be relevant to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SY (Systems and Control).
